![Violin plots with mean and standard deviation for survival, growth, biomass, and net primary productivity among the exotic and native woody species plantations on coal mine spoil. The statistical significance was determined by using student's *t*-test and the *p*-values  <0.0001, <0.001, <0.01, <0.05 and 0.1 corresponds to `****`, `***`, `**`, `*` and `ns`, respectively.](2022-singh-ee_files/figure-html/fig-a-1.svg){#fig-a fig-align='center' width=80%}
:::
:::


### Growth performance

The growth performance of exotic and native species was determined in terms of height and diameter. Height and diameter (growth parameter) were significantly varied among all plantations of exotic and native species (@tbl-b). Among all plantation species (native and exotics), the maximum height was attained by *G. pteridifolia*, whereas maximum diameter was observed for *A. lebbeck* after 5-years of their establishment. The height and diameter values varied from 2.19 to 5.18 m and 4.32 to 7.58 cm, respectively, in native and 2.75 to 5.88 m and 2.99 to 4.90 cm, respectively, in exotic plantations (@tbl-c). However, the height was significantly higher, and the diameter was significantly smaller in exotic species plantations than native species plantations (@fig-a).


::: {#tbl-c .cell layout-align="center" tbl-cap='Growth performance of 5-yr-old planted exotic and native woody species on coal mine spoil'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
