Consequently, the height to diameter ratio was significantly smaller in native species. A significant positive correlation is observed for height and diameter in exotic species, whereas selected native species did not exhibit any significant correlation (@fig-b a). Further, non-legumes showed a significant negative correlation (@fig-b b).


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Relationship between Height and Diameter for exotic and native woody species (a), and legume and non-leguminous species plantations (b). The regression line was fitted using the linear model, and Pearson's correlation coefficient values are represented by letter '*R*' with corresponding probability *p*-values.](2022-singh-ee_files/figure-html/fig-b-1.svg){#fig-b fig-align='center' width=80%}
:::
:::


### Biomass production

The observed values for the biomass of different plant components are summarised in @tbl-d. It was noted that *D. strictus* had shown the highest total biomass production among all the species, whereas *A. auriculiformis* exhibited the highest total biomass production among the exotic species. The biomass of different plant components was significantly varied due to species among all the plantations (@tbl-b). Therefore, values in native plantations significantly varied from 7.68 to 74.68 t ha^-1^, minimum for *T. grandis* and maximum for *D. strictus* plantation and 8.49-31.03 t ha^-1^ exotic plantations, being maximum in *A. auriculiformis* and minimum in *C. siamea* (@tbl-d).


::: {#tbl-d .cell layout-align="center" tbl-cap='Biomass production (t / ha) under 5-yr old planted exotic and native woody species on coal mine spoil'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
